      "title": "See also"
    },
    {
      "blocks": [
        {
          "inline": [
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": "The discrete convolution operation is defined as"
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "formulas": [
            "(a * v)_n = \\sum_{m = -\\infty}^{\\infty} a_m v_{n - m}"
          ],
          "type": "math_block"
        },
        {
          "inline": [
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": "It can be shown that a convolution "
            },
            {
              "kind": "math",
              "latex": "x(t) * y(t)"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": " in time/space\nis equivalent to the multiplication "
            },
            {
              "kind": "math",
              "latex": "X(f) Y(f)"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": " in the Fourier\ndomain, after appropriate padding (padding is necessary to prevent\ncircular convolution).  Since multiplication is more efficient (faster)\nthan convolution, the function "
            },
            {
              "external_url": "https://docs.scipy.org/doc/scipy/reference/generated/scipy.signal.fftconvolve.html",
              "href": "",
              "kind": "link",
              "target": "scipy.signal.fftconvolve",
              "text": "scipy.signal.fftconvolve"
            },
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": " exploits the\nFFT to calculate the convolution of large data-sets."
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        }
      ],
      "title": "Notes"
    },
    {
      "blocks": [
        {
          "raw_kind": "footnote",
          "raw_text": "1\n\nWikipedia, \"Convolution\",\nhttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Convolution",
          "type": "raw_block"
        }
      ],
      "title": "References"
    },
    {
      "blocks": [
        {
          "inline": [
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": "Note how the convolution operator flips the second array\nbefore \"sliding\" the two across one another:"
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "lines": [
            {
              "kind": "input",
              "prompt": ">>>",
              "text": "import whest as we"
            },
            {
              "kind": "input",
              "prompt": ">>>",
              "text": "we.convolve([1, 2, 3], [0, 1, 0.5])"
            },
            {
              "kind": "output",
              "text": "array([0. , 1. , 2.5, 4. , 1.5])"
            }
          ],
          "type": "doctest_block"
        },
        {
          "inline": [
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": "Only return the middle values of the convolution.\nContains boundary effects, where zeros are taken\ninto account:"
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "lines": [
            {
              "kind": "input",
              "prompt": ">>>",
              "text": "we.convolve([1,2,3],[0,1,0.5], 'same')"
            },
            {
              "kind": "output",
              "text": "array([1. ,  2.5,  4. ])"
            }
          ],
          "type": "doctest_block"
        },
        {
          "inline": [
            {
              "kind": "text",
              "text": "The two arrays are of the same length, so there\nis only one position where they completely overlap:"
            }
          ],
          "type": "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "lines": [
            {
              "kind": "input",
              "prompt": ">>>",
              "text": "we.convolve([1,2,3],[0,1,0.5], 'valid')"
            },
            {
              "kind": "output",
              "text": "array([2.5])"
            }
          ],
          "type": "doctest_block"
        }
      ],
      "title": "Examples"
    }
  ],
